  "prompt": "Can people with Down's syndrome have a high IQ? Explain.",
  "response": "While individuals with Down syndrome typically have intellectual disabilities, the severity and level of cognitive functioning can vary widely among individuals. Here are some key points:\n\n1. Intellectual Disability Range\n- Most people with Down syndrome have mild to moderate intellectual disabilities\n- IQ scores often range between 30-70, compared to the average of 100\n- Some individuals can have higher cognitive functioning\n\n2. Factors Influencing Cognitive Potential\n- Early intervention\n- Quality of education\n- Supportive environment\n- Individual genetic variations\n- Access to therapies and learning resources\n\n3. Higher Functioning Individuals\n- Some people with Down syndrome can:\n- Learn to read and write\n- Complete high school\n- Hold jobs\n- Live semi-independently\n- A small percentage may have higher cognitive abilities\n\n4. Cognitive Strengths\n- Many have strong visual learning skills\n- Good social intelligence\n- Strong adaptive and practical skills\n- Emotional intelligence\n\n5. Medical Advancements\n- Improved healthcare\n- Better educational strategies\n- Enhanced support systems\n- These have helped improve cognitive outcomes\n\nWhile a \"high IQ\" is rare, individual potential varies, and many people with Down syndrome can develop significant cognitive and life skills with proper support and opportunities.",
